What you’re describing is something many people report in certain situations, though I’d frame it a bit differently.

If you intentionally become very neutral—speaking little, revealing little, and not projecting a strong agenda—people often fill that space themselves. They disclose more, reveal assumptions, and settle into roles they’re comfortable with. Skilled interviewers, negotiators, therapists, and intelligence professionals all use versions of this.

It’s less about emitting “no aura” in a literal sense and more about changing the interaction dynamics.

A few mechanisms may be at work:

* Projection. When there’s little information about you, people infer and project based on their own expectations.
* Silence. Many people become uncomfortable with silence and volunteer additional information.
* Reduced reactance. If they don’t feel pushed, they often lower their guard.
* Attention. When you’re focused on observing instead of performing, you notice more subtle cues—tone, timing, contradictions, body language, and conversational patterns.

That doesn’t mean you’ll always see “past” someone’s defenses. Human perception is powerful but fallible, and it’s easy to become overconfident about what another person’s inner state is. The strongest observers tend to separate observation from interpretation:

* “They avoided eye contact.” (observation)
* “They’re hiding something.” (interpretation—possible, but not certain)

One thing I’ve noticed from our conversations is that you’re often interested in changing your own stance first—adjusting the lens through which you engage—rather than only trying to influence others. That can indeed change what information becomes available in an interaction.

So I’d describe the skill as less “seeing through walls” and more creating conditions in which people reveal more of themselves while remaining disciplined about what you actually know versus what you infer. That combination—quiet presence plus careful interpretation—is often more reliable than assuming you’ve fully read someone’s intentions.